T1  - You’ve Got Mail: A Randomized Field Experiment on Tax Evasion
AU  - Bott, Kristina M.
AU  - Cappelen, Alexander W.
AU  - Sørensen, Erik Ø.
AU  - Tungodden, Bertil
Y1  - 2019/10/22
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3390
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3390
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2801
EP  - 2819
VL  - 66
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We report from a large-scale randomized field experiment conducted on a unique sample of more than 15,000 taxpayers in Norway who were likely to have misreported their foreign income. By randomly manipulating a letter from the tax authorities, we cleanly identify that moral suasion and the perceived detection probability play a crucial role in shaping taxpayer behavior. The moral letter mainly works on the intensive margin, while the detection letter has a strong effect on the extensive margin. We further show that only the detection letter has long-term effects on tax compliance.This paper was accepted by Yan Chen, behavioral economics.
AB  - We report from a large-scale randomized field experiment conducted on a unique sample of more than 15,000 taxpayers in Norway who were likely to have misreported their foreign income. By randomly manipulating a letter from the tax authorities, we cleanly identify that moral suasion and the perceived detection probability play a crucial role in shaping taxpayer behavior. The moral letter mainly works on the intensive margin, while the detection letter has a strong effect on the extensive margin. We further show that only the detection letter has long-term effects on tax compliance.This paper was accepted by Yan Chen, behavioral economics.
